The reason why using APR to calculate your costs here is silly is because you're making something simple very complicated. APR is used to calculate how much the interest on something will cost you in the long run. This service costs you 1 dollar a month, that's it.

So let me explain, APR means average percentag rate and is a calculation of the percentage of the principal you pay every year as the cost of the interest. Now, assuming you just used this service once and only once, you pay a grand total of 1.33% in interest. APR = 1.33%

1.33% for one month is still an APR (a stands for annual) of 16%. A credit card that you pay off every month allows for a larger advance for a lower price
